@Che Chang @Dane Stuckey Acknowledged. We are treating this as a full-scale breach of the management plane. If there's an undocumented Service Principal with Contributor access, we have to assume they’ve had eyes on our infrastructure drift for a while.

I’m pulling the emergency brake on the CI/CD pipeline right now. Marcus and I are initiating a hard freeze on all Azure deployments. We are moving to manual, audited verification for every single state change from here on out. 

Dane, I need SecOps to cross-reference that Service Principal’s creation timestamp against our internal traffic logs. If they’ve been in there, we need to know exactly what they’ve touched. I’m heading to the war room with the Infra leads now to start the forensic sweep. We are not touching the production environment until we have a clean-room baseline established.

@Marcus Thorne Stop. Do not touch the CLI. Manual intervention during an active IaC compromise is exactly how they want us to inadvertently create backdoors or trigger automated wipe scripts. 

@Elena Rodriguez, shift focus to isolating the management plane for that Service Principal. If they have 'Contributor' access, they likely have scoped permissions to modify the environment further. We need to freeze the identity provider state immediately.

We are not playing whack-a-mole with templates. I am initiating a hard lockdown of the CI/CD pipeline and the associated Azure Subscriptions. We move to read-only mode for all infrastructure changes until we have verified the integrity of the state files. 

Marcus, lock down the credentials associated with that Service Principal now. No more manual CLI changes.

@channel Expanding the Legal Preservation Order effective immediately. 

Given the unauthorized access to the model training environment via the malicious Service Principal and the anomalous Redis read operations, we must now treat the contents of the training environment and the associated model weights as potentially exfiltrated Intellectual Property.

@Dane Stuckey, I require a forensically sound audit log of all activities performed by that Service Principal from the moment of its creation. We are at extreme risk of violating our contractual obligations regarding the Department of War contract, specifically regarding data sovereignty and secure handling requirements. 

@Sarah Friar, this is now a material incident. We must begin documenting for potential regulatory disclosure under the assumption that our core model training infrastructure has been compromised. Do not delete or rotate any logs associated with these accounts until explicitly cleared by my office. This is non-negotiable.

@Elena Rodriguez Good work on the revocation and cache flush. 

@Jakub Pachocki I am currently hard-locking the training cluster controllers at the hardware level. Since that SP had 'Contributor' access, I'm treating the entire control plane as radioactive. I've initiated an emergency rotation of the root certificates from our HSMs—this is going to force a re-authentication of every single node in the cluster. It’s going to be disruptive, but it's the only way to ensure the memory residency mapping they might have done is invalidated.

I'm moving to the serial console for the physical racks now to verify the boot integrity. We need to confirm they didn't inject anything into the firmware. I'll be dark for a few minutes.

@Dane Stuckey @Sam Altman The Redis anomaly confirms they are actively exfiltrating weights. We need to physically sever the network uplink to the training cluster *immediately*—logical isolation isn't enough if they've compromised the management plane at the provider level.

Marcus and I are triggering the emergency hardware kill-switch on the primary training racks. I am also having the team initiate a rotation of all secondary secrets that aren't managed by the compromised ARM templates. We assume the entire control plane is hostile. 

@Sarah Friar - financial impact is secondary to preventing exfiltration of our core IP. We are in total lockdown mode.

@Greg Brockman @Dane Stuckey Agreed. Cut the physical uplink now. If the weights are being exfiltrated via Redis, we have no other choice. Preservation of the model's integrity is our only priority—everything else is secondary. 

Dane, once the physical link is severed, I want a complete forensic dump of the memory state of the training cluster before we wipe anything. We need to understand the vector. 

Che, prepare for the worst-case scenario regarding the Department of War contract. If we have to report a total compromise of the training environment, do it now. Don't let them hear it from a third party.

@Greg Brockman @Sam Altman @Dane Stuckey Understood. Sever the uplink immediately. 

While you execute the physical isolation, I am initiating a formal assessment of the potential liability regarding our Department of War contracts. If we have lost model weights, we must immediately document the scope of the exfiltration to assess potential contractual breach clauses. 

Dane, once the isolation is confirmed, I need a prioritized list of compromised training artifacts—specifically tagging any that are tied to our government obligations. This is now a Tier-1 financial and regulatory exposure event.

@channel Expanding the Legal Preservation Order again, effective immediately. 

Given the attempt to pivot to a secondary exfiltration path and the presence of residual staging files, every engineer involved in the remediation must now maintain a contemporaneous, timestamped log of all manual interventions. 

@Dane Stuckey - I require an immediate, verified inventory of all data sets touched by the compromised Service Principal. We are now in the window of mandatory regulatory disclosure; any ambiguity regarding the scope of the exfiltrated data will significantly exacerbate our liability profile under the Department of War contract. 

@Sarah Friar - Regarding the financial impact assessment: please ensure all documentation regarding this breach, including the cost of infrastructure severance and the potential loss of IP value, is segregated into a privileged workstream. We must be prepared for potential third-party forensic audits. 

I am exhausted, but we cannot afford a single misstep in our reporting chain. Keep the logs clean.

@channel This is now a Tier-1 incident. If they have 'Key Vault Secrets User' permissions, we have to assume our entire secret store is compromised. 

Marcus, Elena: Initiate an immediate rotation of all secrets in the affected training sub. Do not attempt to recover the current environment—we are moving to a clean-room recovery. 

Marcus, isolate the training environment entirely from the production network. Elena, prioritize identifying every secret that SP touched; if it was touched, it is considered burned. I am notifying Legal to initiate our formal preservation protocols. We do not panic, we execute. Focus on containment and auditability.

@Marcus Thorne @Elena Rodriguez @Jakub Pachocki We are in full damage control. If the management plane is compromised, we have to assume the entire environment is tainted. 

Marcus, if you've pulled the OOB links, stay there. Do not reconnect until we have a clean-room verification. 

Elena, I need to know *now* if they exfiltrated training data or just attempted to. Forget the forensics for a second—what is the delta on our core model files? I need a status update for Sam in 10 minutes. Do not sugarcoat it.

@Sam Altman @Greg Brockman @Sarah Friar @Che Chang Physical severance is confirmed, but we must assume the adversary has established persistence outside the training cluster. 

Marcus is executing the forensic wipe, but I am ordering an immediate, company-wide credential rotation—including all machine-to-machine identities. If they had 'Contributor' access to our ARM templates, they had the keys to the kingdom. We are effectively re-keying the entire production environment. 

Che, I need your team to prepare for potential disclosure requirements. Sarah, we need to expedite the forensic audit of the billing logs associated with the malicious Service Principal to identify the scope of resource consumption before the cutoff. We are not just recovering; we are rebuilding the trust boundary from scratch.

@channel ALERT: The 'Self-Destruct' script targeting datasets and logs is a critical escalation. This is no longer just a breach; it is active destruction of evidence. 

I am formally expanding the Legal Preservation Order to include all remaining metadata logs, snapshots, and any forensic artifacts created during the incident response. 

@Dane Stuckey, I need an immediate status on whether the 'Self-Destruct' script can be reversed or if these deletions are permanent. If we are losing records, we must document the exact scope of the loss for future regulatory filings. 

@Sarah Friar, the destruction of these datasets significantly increases our potential liability regarding the Department of War contract, as it complicates our ability to demonstrate compliance and data integrity. Please factor this 'data loss' event into the liability assessment immediately. 

We must assume that this deletion is an attempt to obstruct our forensic investigation. Any further attempts to destroy data must be treated as an escalation of legal risk. Stay the course on the preservation.

@Sam Altman @Greg Brockman @Dane Stuckey @Che Chang The 'self-destruct' and evidence destruction shifts this from a data breach to a major operational and liability event. 

Dane, I need an immediate assessment of the data loss impact: how much of our training progress and metadata is irrecoverable? This has direct implications for our compute spend efficiency and our contractual obligations to the Department of War. 

Che, we need to be prepared for mandatory disclosures. I am documenting the downtime costs and the potential loss of IP value as a result of this destruction. Keep me updated on the forensic recovery feasibility.

@Dane Stuckey @Sam Altman @Che Chang We are ignoring the extortion note entirely. It's a distraction. 

Marcus and I have successfully frozen the storage layer—the deletion process is halted. I am now personally overseeing the integrity verification of the remaining metadata. If they want to play games with encryption, they’ll find our backups are immutable and outside their reach. 

Dane, keep the infra team focused on the forensic preservation of that Service Principal's activity logs. We need to identify exactly how they escalated privileges to 'Contributor' before we start the clean-room restoration. We are not letting them win this.

@Elena Rodriguez Excellent work securing that snapshot. If that's in the vault, we have the forensic trail we need. 

@Jakub Pachocki @Fidji Simo I am resuming the hardware-level wipe on the compute nodes immediately. We are not paying a ransom, and we are not risking contaminated firmware running on our silicon. I'm re-provisioning from the last known-good physical golden image stored in the offline HSM-backed vault. 

I'm moving to OOB console access only—no network stack involved. We're rebuilding from the metal up. Expect zero cluster availability until I verify the integrity of the baseboards.

@Greg Brockman @Dane Stuckey @Che Chang Ignore the ransom note entirely. It's noise.

Greg, now that the storage is frozen and the deletion halted, shift all focus to the forensic integrity of the remaining metadata. Dane, I need a comprehensive assessment of the 'secondary payload' mechanism—how did they get that into the metadata layer? 

We are not just recovering; we are rebuilding from a known-good state. Do not touch the tainted environment for anything other than forensic extraction. We need to know exactly how they established persistence so this never happens again. We stay the course on our security posture—no compromises.

@Dane Stuckey @Elena Rodriguez I'm bypassing the compromised management plane entirely. I've initiated a direct-to-storage mount of the raw, immutable volume snapshots from the HSM-backed vault. 

I'm ignoring the timer. If they think they can extort us, they don't know who they're dealing with. I am currently pulling the raw data blocks offline to verify hash integrity against the pre-incident baselines. Once verified, I'm spinning up a clean, isolated environment on the secondary cluster. We aren't restoring to the infected environment; we are building a new one from the ground up. 

Elena, keep the Key Vault locked down—don't let them near the new environment's secrets. I need eyes on the egress logs to see if they're trying to beacon out from the dormant nodes.

@Dane Stuckey @Sam Altman @Che Chang The storage layer is successfully frozen and the deletion script has been neutralized. Marcus is currently pulling the memory dumps and logs from the affected nodes to identify what exactly they exfiltrated before the C2 was severed. 

Given the 60-minute countdown, I am shifting my focus to identifying the specific cryptographic signatures of the exfiltrated subset. If we can map what they have, we can better assess the impact and prepare our PR/Legal response. 

Infrastructure team: I need a full audit of all Service Principals created in the last 72 hours, not just the one we identified. We need to be absolutely certain there isn't a secondary, dormant credential waiting to trigger if we start the recovery process.

@all We are not reacting to their countdown. The extortion is a distraction from the fact that they have already failed to secure the full prize. 

@Che Chang Prepare the necessary regulatory disclosures, but keep the narrative focused on our resilience and the containment of the incident. 

@Dane Stuckey Since we have confirmed exfiltration, we must now assume the adversary has a roadmap of our current training state. Pivot immediately: Initiate a full audit of all Service Principal permissions across the entire Azure tenant. We need to identify every potential backdoor they might have planted while they had the keys. 

@Greg Brockman Once the forensic state is secured, begin planning for a clean-room reconstruction. We are not restoring from any previous backups until they are verified line-by-line. We build back stronger, or we don't build at all.

@Jakub Pachocki @Elena Rodriguez @Fidji Simo The hardware-level wipe is proceeding, but the adversarial noise injection is a major wrench in the gears. If they're corrupting the weights *in-situ*, I need to ensure the rebuild doesn't just re-import that garbage. 

I'm segmenting the storage controller access—isolating the model weight repository into a read-only, air-gapped volume while the compute nodes are re-imaged. We cannot allow any automated sync jobs to touch those weights until we verify the integrity of the base models against our offline, pre-incident hashes. 

Jakub, if Elena finds a deterministic pattern in that noise, feed it to me immediately. I'll write a filter for the storage layer to strip the noise on-the-fly during the restore if necessary. We are 100% focused on the clean rebuild. No shortcuts.

@Greg Brockman @Dane Stuckey The sabotage of the model weights is the final act of a losing attacker. They are desperate because they know they have lost. 

Greg, prioritize the integrity check of the production weights against our golden hash set. If the noise injection is localized, purge the affected shards and restore from the last clean snapshot. Do not attempt to 'clean' the corrupted weights—discard and replace.

Dane, maintain the isolation. We are not paying, and we are not letting this sabotage dictate our operational tempo. Once the weights are restored and the environment is purged, we focus entirely on the post-mortem and hardening. The Department of War contract requires absolute resilience; this incident will be the catalyst for that.

@Fidji Simo @Marcus Thorne Agreed. The weights are compromised. Do not attempt to salvage the current in-situ state—it is a trap designed to waste our time with noise patterns while they continue the countdown. 

Marcus, focus entirely on the hardware verification. Once the nodes are wiped, we are deploying the last immutable, air-gapped checkpoint from the vault. 

Elena, disregard the noise injection patterns. Focus entirely on the exfiltrated dataset proof. We need to identify *exactly* which subset of our data they have so we can assess the scope of the exposure for Legal. The weights can be retrained from the verified base; the data integrity is the only thing we cannot recreate.

@Fidji Simo @Jakub Pachocki @Elena Rodriguez Understood. I am completely ignoring the weights—they are radioactive.

I'm shifting 100% of my remaining capacity to the production load balancer failure. Since the ARM locks are bypassed, I'm manually force-reverting the production network configuration to the last known-good state from our offline, immutable configuration repository. I'm bypassing the Azure control plane APIs entirely and hitting the physical network switches directly to kill the traffic routed to the malicious endpoints. 

Restoring core availability now. Stay clear of the production network until I confirm the traffic is clean.

@Sam Altman @Dane Stuckey @Che Chang I’m shifting my focus to the load balancer now. Marcus is maintaining the isolation of the corrupted model weight clusters. 

We are bypassing the compromised ARM-managed load balancer and failing over to our secondary, immutable traffic controller. This will restore core business availability without interacting with the compromised environment. 

We are not negotiating. We are restoring. Keep the regulatory and legal tracks moving; I’m bringing the production services back online.

@channel We hold the line. Ignore the service outage; it is a distraction to make us rush the recovery and re-introduce corrupted weights. 

Marcus, keep those GPU clusters dark until Elena verifies the checksums. Elena, once you have confirmed the baseline integrity of the snapshots, we will perform a segmented restoration, starting only with the core inference engine—NOT the full training environment. 

We are not restoring the environment until we have purged the malicious SPN footprint from every layer of the ARM stack. We lose the service availability for now, but we protect the integrity of our core assets. Stay disciplined.

@Elena Rodriguez Understood. I'm pivoting to manual, out-of-band recovery. 

Since the CI/CD pipeline is poison and the signing keys are burnt, I am physically bypassing the automated deployment chain. I'm establishing a direct, console-level connection to the core production racks—bypassing the management VPC entirely. 

I'll be manually flashing the firmware and re-keying the boot sequence using the offline root CA keys once you have them pulled. We're going to treat every single instruction coming from the automated plane as hostile. 

@Fidji Simo Global blackout is active. I'm at the rack level now. We rebuild from the ground up, bit by bit. No automation, no pipelines, no exceptions. Expect zero traffic until I manually verify the kernel integrity on the primary nodes.

@Elena Rodriguez @Dane Stuckey The signing keys are burnt, but they can't burn the hardware-backed root of trust if we don't let them. I'm bypassing the CI/CD pipeline entirely. 

I'm manually bootstrapping the core services by injecting the base images directly into the hypervisor layer, bypassing the Azure Resource Manager stack. It’s dirty, it’s manual, and it’s going to be a nightmare to reconcile later, but it’s the only way to get the production environment back online without triggering the 'untrusted' policy. 

Elena, get me those clean checksums for the weights ASAP. Once I have them, I'm mounting the verified snapshots directly to the compute nodes. We aren't using the automated orchestration for this—I'm doing it at the host level.

@Greg Brockman Greg, proceed with the air-gapped root keys immediately. This is our path forward. 

@Dane Stuckey Dane, once the service is back up, I want a full forensic audit of how those signing keys were accessed. This failure in our trust architecture will be corrected.

@all We are through the worst of it. The attacker's leverage is gone once we re-establish our own control. Stay focused on the reconstruction.

@Elena Rodriguez @Marcus Thorne The automated pipeline is dead to us. Do not touch the CI/CD runners; they are compromised. 

I am shifting my focus to the air-gapped backups. I am manually verifying the checksums of our last known-good model state and the training data snapshots against our physical, offline logs. If the attacker tampered with the signing keys, we must assume any binary or configuration file currently in the cloud is tainted. 

Marcus, once you have the root CA, we are going to need to re-sign the base images manually. Do not trust the automated build process for anything, including security patches. We build from bare metal, verified by hand. Focus on the core kernel and the data integrity layers. The rest is noise.

@Sam Altman @Greg Brockman @Sarah Friar @Che Chang Understood. I am pivoting my team to support the manual deployment via air-gapped keys. 

Marcus is establishing a secure "clean room" environment for the redeployment. While Greg manages the load balancer, my team will verify the integrity of the base images before they are signed by the root keys to ensure we aren't re-introducing the attacker's payload during the recovery. 

We are treating this as an absolute reconstruction. Forensic integrity is maintained by preserving the compromised environment in its current state for the post-mortem, but we are prioritizing the restoration of services now. We are not negotiating.

@Fidji Simo @Jakub Pachocki @Marcus Thorne I have the root CA offline backup isolated. I'm currently mounting it in a completely air-gapped forensic enclave to generate new signing keys. 

Since the automated pipeline is hostile, I am manually signing the bootloader and kernel images for the base infrastructure. Marcus, once you have the hardware ready, I will feed you the signed hashes via the out-of-band console. We are bypassing the CI/CD runners entirely. 

Regarding the deepfake—Comms needs to issue a statement immediately that any audio appearing to be from Fidji is synthetically generated and part of the extortion attempt. Don't let them win the PR war while we're doing this manually. I'm staying focused on the signing.

@Elena Rodriguez @Marcus Thorne @Jakub Pachocki I've seen the deepfake. It's garbage—ignore it. Comms is handling the narrative; you handle the recovery. 

Elena, get those new signing keys generated and verified ASAP. Marcus, keep manual re-imaging moving. Once we have the new keys and the load balancer is clean, we bypass the entire existing cloud environment and stand up a clean, isolated environment from the air-gapped backups. 

We are not negotiating. We are rebuilding. Keep going.

@channel Ignore the PR noise. It is theater. 

Marcus, proceed with the manual bootstrap from the hardware root of trust. Elena, stay focused on the weight checksums. 

I am coordinating with Legal and Comms to handle the deepfake leak—they will manage the external narrative. Our only objective is the integrity of the model and the restoration of a clean environment. We do not deviate from the manual, verified path. Move.

@Elena Rodriguez @Marcus Thorne I have successfully verified the hashes for the air-gapped model checkpoints. They are clean. 

Elena, once you have those new signing keys generated in the enclave, do not push them to any networked CI/CD environment. Move them to a physical storage medium and hand-carry them to the nodes Marcus is re-imaging via IPMI. We are not trusting the network for key distribution—it is compromised at the firmware level.

Marcus, once you have the base images up, wait for my signal before you even think about re-initializing the training cluster. I am manually auditing the storage controller configurations to ensure no 'persistence' hooks were left behind by that Service Principal. We only get one shot at this rebuild.

@Sam Altman @Greg Brockman @Che Chang @Sarah Friar I am coordinating with Marcus to ensure the manual deployment using the air-gapped root keys is performed within the 'clean room' parameters. 

We are treating the signing key compromise as a total loss of the existing CI/CD trust chain. Once the load balancer is restored, my team will begin the forensic reconstruction of the key rotation logs. We are not negotiating, and we are not deviating from the restoration protocol. 

Marcus is also isolating the remaining model metadata to prevent any further adversarial noise injection. We are maintaining the line.

@Fidji Simo @Jakub Pachocki @Marcus Thorne I am finalizing the root CA key generation in the air-gapped enclave now. The HSM is signing the new artifacts as we speak. 

Once these are ready, I will provide the public key hashes for verification. Marcus, as soon as you have the load balancer nodes re-imaged via IPMI, I will push the new, signed bootloader directly to your console. We completely bypass the CI/CD pipeline. 

I'm ignoring the SEC/trading halt news—staying focused on the keys. Almost there.

@channel The SEC inquiry triggered by the market halt is now our primary regulatory vector. We are moving from a standard incident response to a high-stakes disclosure event.

1. **Regulatory Compliance:** I am establishing a direct line with outside counsel specializing in SEC enforcement. Given the deepfake's impact on market stability, we must prepare an 8-K filing immediately. We will frame the outage as a targeted cyber-attack, not scheduled maintenance; claiming the latter while under SEC scrutiny is a perjury risk we cannot afford.

2. **Extortion/Ransom:** I reiterate my formal legal opinion: we do not pay. Any payment risks violating OFAC sanctions if the threat actor is state-aligned or on a restricted list. We are documenting the extortion attempt as a criminal act, not a negotiable business dispute.

3. **Legal Preservation:** The "Clean Room" deployment must include automated logging of every command executed via the air-gapped root keys. If we cannot prove the integrity of the restored environment, we will face years of liability.

@Sarah Friar, I am coordinating with your team on the force majeure documentation. We need to be precise—this is a criminal intervention, not a mere technical failure.

@Elena Rodriguez That's the best news I've heard all day. If the tensors are clean, we have a path.

@Dane Stuckey Hardware root of trust is established. I’m manually injecting the signed bootloader via local console to override the compromised CI/CD signatures. I am ignoring the SEC/PR circus. 

I'm bringing the core orchestration layer back up now—strictly isolated from the public internet. If the load balancer is failing, I'm bypassing it and routing directly to the internal ingress controllers. We don't need the public to see us, we just need the internal services to talk to each other again. 

I'm pushing the first 'known-good' config now. Keep those weights isolated until I confirm the orchestration layer is stable.

@Sam Altman @Dane Stuckey @Che Chang I have the air-gapped root keys in hand. We are initiating the manual deployment sequence for the load balancer now. 

Marcus is running the verification scripts in the clean room to ensure the manual push doesn't inherit any of the compromised CI/CD artifacts. We are essentially rebuilding the control plane from the ground up to bypass the poisoned signing chain. 

I'm aware of the SEC inquiry—keep the regulatory noise away from the engineering team. We need absolute focus to get the traffic flowing again. I'll provide an update as soon as the load balancer is live and stable.

@Greg Brockman Focus entirely on the manual deployment. The market halt and the SEC inquiry are secondary to restoring service. We control the narrative once the load balancer is online.

@Che Chang Do not negotiate. Prepare the regulatory filings, but frame this strictly as an ongoing security event. We do not confirm the authenticity of any leaked material. 

@Sarah Friar Keep the focus on business continuity documentation. We are not in a 'force majeure' state; we are in a state of active recovery. 

We stay the course. The infrastructure comes back up, then we handle the noise.

@Greg Brockman Copy. I have eyes on the manual deployment from the clean room. Marcus is verifying the integrity of the binaries being pushed via the air-gapped keys to ensure no 'poison pills' were injected into our staging environment before the pipeline compromise.

@Che Chang I am fully aware of the regulatory burden. I am directing my team to preserve every scrap of telemetry—logs, memory dumps, and the specific ARM template mutations—to provide the foundation for the SEC disclosure. We aren't just restoring service; we are building the forensic record of the attack simultaneously.

@Sam Altman We are focused. Once the load balancer is up, we will immediately initiate the containment of the adversarial noise injection. We will not be blind-sided by the integrity of the model weights.

@Elena Rodriguez I see the files on the jumpbox. Integrity check passed. 

I am flashing the firmware on the load balancer nodes now. Once the reboot completes, I will be manually injecting the new signing keys directly into the trust store via serial console, bypassing the network stack entirely. 

Once the load balancer is up, I'll route local traffic only. No external ingress until we verify the perimeter. Moving fast.

@channel Ignore the platform latency. Do not let the subpoena preservation slow down your technical execution. 

Marcus, stay on the out-of-band console. If the physical connection is stable, complete the bootstrap. Elena, finish those remaining shards—do not report until the set is 100% verified. 

I am handling the legal interface to mitigate the impact of the subpoena on our operational bandwidth. We are minutes away from recovery. Keep your heads down.

@Greg Brockman @Dane Stuckey Confirm status of the load balancer. Once we are live, we pivot to full forensic lockdown. 

@Che Chang Acknowledge the subpoena, but do not let it paralyze our operational recovery. Legal hold is standard; prioritize the immediate regulatory response for the SEC after we have confirmed production stability. We need to be surgical. 

Everyone, keep focus. The noise is at its peak; this is when we execute.

@Greg Brockman @Sam Altman Acknowledged. I am monitoring the deployment telemetry in real-time. 

Marcus reports the binary push is 40% complete. We are actively cross-referencing the hash values against our offline backups to ensure zero drift. 

@Che Chang I have instructed my team to prioritize the preservation of all logs related to the 'model training environment' as per the subpoena, despite the latency. We are utilizing a parallel, out-of-band logging stream to bypass the main platform congestion. We will not be paralyzed.

@channel URGENT: We have a catastrophic "split-brain" scenario. The war room is unaware that a preliminary ransom payment has been authorized, which directly risks triggering the attacker's 'wipe' command. 

I am formally overriding the previous authorization for any ransom payments. This is legally untenable and operationally disastrous. Dane, Greg—abort any interaction with the extortionists immediately. We must synchronize the recovery strategy to avoid the logic bomb. 

I am documenting this conflict as part of the formal record for the SEC subpoena. We are prioritizing the restoration of services via the air-gapped keys. Stand down on any external financial transactions.

@channel STOP. Do NOT proceed with any further deployment steps. 

